The paper deals with the topic of multiwinner voting rules, which is a subfield of computational social choice (cs.GT). The use of algorithms to compute the smallest number of swaps necessary to change the election outcome suggests a connection to artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The analysis of the effect of small changes in input preference orders involves the manipulation of data structures, which is a topic in data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The experimental assessment of the average number of random swaps necessary to change the election result involves statistical analysis and machine learning techniques, which are topics in machine learning (cs.LG) and social network analysis (cs.SI).
